\begin{node}
We need some helper functions for taking the union of hypotheses
$\Gamma_{1}\cup\Gamma_{2}$ (implemented as ``[[Gamma1 @@ Gamma2]]'')
and removing hypotheses $\Gamma\setminus\{\phi\}$ (implemented as``[[remove phi Gamma]]'').
I think a slightly more optimized version would sort the hypotheses,
to remove duplicate entries faster. But this would add
an additional $\bigOh(n\log n)$ runtime to each invocation.
\end{node}

<<Inference rules>>=
infix @@
fun [] @@ ys = ys
  | xs @@ [] = xs
  | xs @@ ys = xs @ ys;

fun remove phi Gamma =
  List.filter (not o (Formula.eq phi)) Gamma;
@ %def @@ remove

\begin{node}
We have the inference rules related to assumptions:
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\texttt{assume}(\phi,\Gamma)]{\phi,\Gamma\vdash\phi}{}}
\end{equation}
Discharging is the same as ``implication introduction'' according to
Kleene's \textit{Introduction to Mathematical Logic} (\S11, p.44):
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\texttt{disch}(\phi)]{\Gamma\setminus\{\phi\}\vdash\phi\implies\psi}{\Gamma\vdash\psi,&\phi\in\Gamma}}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\texttt{undisch}]{\phi,\Gamma\vdash\psi}{\Gamma\vdash\phi\implies\psi}}
\end{equation}
The \textit{modus ponens} is really the same thing as ``implication elimination''
(again, by Kleene, \textit{ibid}):
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\texttt{modus\_ponens}]{\Gamma_{1}\cup\Gamma_{2}\vdash\psi}{\Gamma_{1}\vdash\phi\implies\psi,&\Gamma_{2}\vdash\phi}}
\end{equation}
The other inference rules for connectives are straightforward
``introduction'' and ``elimination'' rules.
\end{node}

<<Specification for inference rules>>=
val assume : Formula.t -> Formula.t list -> t;
val disch : Formula.t -> t -> t;
val undisch : t -> t;
val modus_ponens : t -> t -> t;
@ 
<<Inference rules>>=
fun assume phi Gamma = (phi::Gamma) |- phi;

fun disch phi (Gamma |- psi) = (remove phi Gamma) |- Formula.mk_imp(phi,psi);

fun undisch (Gamma |- A) =
  if not(Formula.is_imp A)
  then raise Fail "Thm.undisch: conclusion must be an implication"
  else let val (phi,psi) = Formula.dest_imp A
       in (phi::Gamma) |- psi end;

fun modus_ponens (Gamma1 |- imp) (Gamma2 |- phi) =
  if not(Formula.is_imp imp)
  then raise Fail("modus_ponens: major premise ("^
                  (Formula.serialize imp)^
                  ") expected implication")
  else let
    val (A, B) = Formula.dest_imp imp
  in
    if not(Formula.eq A phi)
    then raise Fail "modus_ponens: premise does not match argument"
    else (Gamma1 @@ Gamma2) |- B
  end;
@ %def Thm.assume Thm.disch Thm.undisch Thm.modus_ponens

\begin{node}
The rules for conjunction are fairly straightforward. If you have
proven $\phi$ and if you have proven $\psi$, then you can infer
$\phi\land\psi$ provided you take the union of all the local
assumptions. In other words,
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\land\mbox{-intro}]{\Gamma_{1}\cup\Gamma_{2}\vdash\phi\land\psi}{\Gamma_{1}\vdash\phi,&\Gamma_{2}\vdash\psi}}
\end{equation}
Similarly, if we have already proven $\Gamma\vdash\phi\land\psi$, then
we can ``break apart'' the conjunction to get each conjunct.
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\land\mbox{-elim-l}]{\Gamma\vdash\phi}{\Gamma\vdash\phi\land\psi}}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\land\mbox{-elim-r}]{\Gamma\vdash\psi}{\Gamma\vdash\phi\land\psi}}
\end{equation}
\end{node}

<<Specification for inference rules>>=
val and_intro : t -> t -> t;
val and_elim_l : t -> t;
val and_elim_r : t -> t;
@ 

<<Inference rules>>=
fun and_intro (Gamma1 |- phi) (Gamma2 |- psi) =
  (Gamma1 @@ Gamma2) |- Formula.mk_and(phi, psi);

fun and_elim_l (Gamma |- phi) =
  if not(Formula.is_and phi)
  then raise Fail "and_elim_l: expects conjunction"
  else
    let val (A,B) = Formula.dest_and phi
    in Gamma |- A end;

fun and_elim_r (Gamma |- phi) =
  if not(Formula.is_and phi)
  then raise Fail "and_elim_r: expects conjunction"
  else
    let val (A,B) = Formula.dest_and phi
    in Gamma |- B end;
@ %def Thm.and_intro Thm.and_elim_l Thm.and_elim_r

\begin{node}
Disjunction introduction is straightforward: we can always assume ``or
something else'' holds. More precisely,
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\lor\mbox{-intro-l}(\phi)]{\Gamma\vdash\phi\lor\psi}{\Gamma\vdash\psi}}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\lor\mbox{-intro-r}(\psi)]{\Gamma\vdash\phi\lor\psi}{\Gamma\vdash\phi}}
\end{equation}
Disjunction elimination requires some explanation. If we have proven
$\Gamma\vdash A\lor B$ and we want to prove $\Gamma\vdash C$, then we
just need to establish $\Gamma\vdash A\implies C$ and $\Gamma\vdash B\implies C$.
In Mizar, these correspond to the two \texttt{suppose} blocks. The
rule is 
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\lor\mbox{-elim}]{\Gamma_{1}\cup\Gamma_{2}\vdash(A\lor B)\implies C}{\Gamma_{1}\vdash A\implies C,&\Gamma_{2}\vdash B\implies C}}
\end{equation}
If any of the premises mismatch each other (e.g., we have
$\Gamma_{2}\vdash A'\implies C$ for some $A\neq A'$), then an
exception is raised.

Note that there are other variations of $\lor$-elimination which are
logically equivalent to this inference rule. Most texts use the same
inference rule for $\lor$-elimination as found in Classical natural
deduction,
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer{\Gamma\vdash C}{\Gamma\vdash A\lor B, & \Gamma,A\vdash C & \Gamma,B\vdash C}}
\end{equation}
Then discharging $A$ (resp., $B$) in the premises, including $A\lor B\in\Gamma$
and discharging $A\lor B$ from the conclusion, gives us our
$\lor$-elimination rule.
\end{node}

<<Specification for inference rules>>=
val or_intro_l : Formula.t -> t -> t;
val or_intro_r : Formula.t -> t -> t;
val or_elim : t -> t -> t;
@ 

<<Inference rules>>=
fun or_intro_l A (Gamma |- B) = (Gamma |- Formula.mk_or(A, B))

fun or_intro_r B (Gamma |- A) = (Gamma |- Formula.mk_or(A, B))

fun or_elim (Gamma1 |- A_imp_C) (Gamma2 |- B_imp_C) =
  if not(Formula.is_imp A_imp_C)
  then raise Fail "or_elim: first theorem must be an implication"
  else if not(Formula.is_imp B_imp_C)
  then raise Fail "or_elim: second theorem must be an implication"
  else
    let
      val (A,C1) = Formula.dest_imp A_imp_C;
      val (B,C2) = Formula.dest_imp B_imp_C;
      val A_or_B_imp_C = Formula.mk_imp(Formula.mk_or(A, B), C1);
    in
      if not(Formula.eq C1 C2)
      then raise Fail "or_elim: conclusions of theorems disagree"
      else (Gamma1 @@ Gamma2) |- A_or_B_imp_C
    end;
@ %def Thm.or_elim Thm.or_intro_l Thm.or_intro_r

\begin{node}
Negation-related rules follow from ``unfolding'' (and ``folding'') the abbreviation $\neg A\equiv A\implies\bot$
as inference rules.
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\neg\mbox{-intro}]{\Gamma\vdash\neg\phi}{\Gamma\vdash\phi\implies\bot}}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\neg\mbox{-elim}]{\Gamma\vdash\phi\implies\bot}{\Gamma\vdash\neg\phi}}
\end{equation}
\end{node}

<<Specification for inference rules>>=
val not_intro : t -> t;
val not_elim : t -> t;
@

<<Inference rules>>=
fun not_intro (Gamma |- phi_imp_false) =
  if not(Formula.is_imp phi_imp_false)
  then raise Fail "not_intro: theorem is not an implication"
  else let
    val (phi, F) = Formula.dest_imp phi_imp_false;
  in
    if not(Formula.is_falsum F)
    then raise Fail "not_intro: theorem is not 'implies falsum'"
    else Gamma |- Formula.mk_not(phi)
  end;

fun not_elim (Gamma |- not_phi) =
  if not(Formula.is_not not_phi)
  then raise Fail("not_elim: theorem ("^
                  (Formula.serialize not_phi)^
                  ") is not a negation")
  else let
    val (phi) = Formula.dest_not not_phi;
  in
    Gamma |- Formula.mk_imp(phi, Formula.mk_falsum())
  end;
@ %def Thm.not_intro Thm.not_elim

\begin{node}
The Intuitionistic rule for eliminating contradictions is just the
principle of explosion: from a contradiction $\bot$ we can infer
anything. 
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\mbox{contr}(\phi)]{\Gamma\vdash\phi}{\Gamma\vdash\bot}}
\end{equation}
\end{node}

<<Specification for inference rules>>=
val contr : Formula.t -> t -> t;
@

<<Inference rules>>=
fun contr phi (Gamma |- falsum) =
  if not(Formula.is_falsum falsum)
  then raise Fail "contr: theorem is not falsum"
  else Gamma |- phi;
@ %def Thm.contr

\begin{node}
Biconditionals $A\iff B$ may be viewed as an abbreviation for
$(A\implies B)\land(B\implies A)$. The introduction and elimination
rules correspond to the derived rules for the abbreviation.
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\Leftrightarrow\mbox{-intro}]{\Gamma_{1}\cup\Gamma_{2}\vdash\phi\iff\psi}{\Gamma_{1}\vdash\phi\implies\psi,&\Gamma_{2}\vdash\psi\implies\phi}}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\Leftrightarrow\mbox{-elim-l}]{\Gamma\vdash\phi\implies\psi}{\Gamma\vdash\phi\iff\psi}}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\Leftrightarrow\mbox{-elim-r}]{\Gamma\vdash\psi\implies\phi}{\Gamma\vdash\phi\iff\psi}}
\end{equation}
\end{node}

<<Specification for inference rules>>=
val iff_intro : t -> t -> t;
val iff_elim_l : t -> t;
val iff_elim_r : t -> t;
@
<<Inference rules>>=
fun iff_intro (Gamma1 |- A_imp_B) (Gamma2 |- B_imp_A) =
  if not(Formula.is_imp A_imp_B)
  then raise Fail "iff_intro: first theorem is not an implication"
  else if not(Formula.is_imp B_imp_A)
  then raise Fail "iff_intro: second theorem is not an implication"
  else let
    val (A1,B1) = Formula.dest_imp(A_imp_B);
    val (B2,A2) = Formula.dest_imp(B_imp_A);
  in
    if not(Formula.eq A1 A2)
    then raise Fail("iff_intro: premise of first theorem ("^
                    (Formula.serialize A1)^
                    ") is not conclusion of second theorem ("^
                    (Formula.serialize A2)^
                    ")")
    else if not(Formula.eq B1 B2)
    then raise Fail("iff_intro: premise of second theorem ("^
                    (Formula.serialize B2)
                    ^") is not conclusion of first theorem ("^
                    (Formula.serialize B1)
                    ^")")
    else (Gamma1 @@ Gamma2) |- Formula.mk_iff(A1,B2)
  end;

fun iff_elim_l (Gamma |- A_iff_B) =
  if not(Formula.is_iff A_iff_B)
  then raise Fail "iff_elim_l: theorem is not an iff"
  else
    let val (A,B) = Formula.dest_iff A_iff_B
    in Gamma |- Formula.mk_imp(A,B) end;

fun iff_elim_r (Gamma |- A_iff_B) =
  if not(Formula.is_iff A_iff_B)
  then raise Fail "iff_elim_r: theorem is not an iff"
  else
    let val (A,B) = Formula.dest_iff A_iff_B
    in Gamma |- Formula.mk_imp(B,A) end;
@ %def Thm.iff_intro Thm.iff_elim_l Thm.iff_elim_r

\begin{node}[Quantifier inference rules]
We have the inference rule for generalization: given any variable $x$
which does not appear [freely] in the local assumptions $\Gamma$, we
can infer $\forall x\ldotp\phi$ even if $x$ does not appear in $\phi$
(but this is a rather boring situation):
\begin{equation*}
\vcenter{\infer[\forall\mbox{-intro}(x)]{\Gamma\vdash\forall x\ldotp\phi}{\Gamma\vdash\phi,&x\notin FV(\Gamma)}}
\end{equation*}
In particular, this means that we cannot infer from $P[y]\vdash P[y]$ 
the claim $P[y]\vdash\forall y\ldotp P[y]$ unless $y\notin FV(P[y])$
(in which case $\forall y\ldotp P[y]$ is vacuous).
\end{node}

<<Specification for inference rules>>=
val forall_intro : Term.t -> t -> t;
@

<<Inference rules>>=
fun forall_intro (x : Term.t) (Gamma |- phi) =
  if not(Term.is_var x)
  then raise Fail "forall_intro: x is not a variable"
  else let fun free_in fm = List.exists (Term.eq x) (Formula.fv fm);
       in if List.exists free_in Gamma
          then raise Fail "forall_intro: x is free in hypotheses"
          else Gamma |- (Formula.mk_forall(x, phi))
       end;
@ %def Thm.forall_intro

\begin{node}
Universal quantifier elimination is quite simple provided $t$ is free
for $x$ in $\phi[-]$ (i.e., no free variable will become bound in $\phi[t]$):
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\forall\mbox{-elim}]{\Gamma\vdash\phi[t]}{\Gamma\vdash\forall x\ldotp\phi[x]}}
\end{equation}
This is just instantiating a universally quantified variable $x$ with
a term $t$. The only possible source of problems we could encounter is
if $t$ and $x$ have different sorts, which should raise a failure
exception.

A more subtle problem occurs when $t$ has a free variable which would
be captured by a quantifier upon substituting $t$ for $x$ in $P[x]$. 
For example, if $P[x]:=\forall y\ldotp x=y$ and $t=f(y)$, then
$P[f(y)]=\forall y\ldotp f(y)=y$ would result in capturing $y$ in $t=f(y)$.
This \emph{should} be an error, which will be raised in an exception.
\end{node}

<<Specification for inference rules>>=
val forall_elim : Term.t -> t -> t;
@

<<Inference rules>>=
fun forall_elim (t : Term.t) (Gamma |- forall_phi) =
  if not(Formula.is_forall forall_phi)
  then raise Fail "forall_elim: theorem is not universally quantified"
  else let val (x,phi) = Formula.dest_forall forall_phi
       in if not(Formula.free_for t x phi)
          then raise Fail "forall_elim: term is not free for conclusion"
          else Gamma |- (Formula.subst x t phi)
       end;
@ %def Thm.forall_elim

\begin{node}\label{node:kernel.nw:existential-introduction}
Existential introduction has the same proviso as universal quantifier
elimination---$t$ is free for $x$ in $\phi[-]$:
\begin{equation}
\vcenter{\infer[\exists\mbox{-intro}]{\Gamma\vdash\exists x\ldotp\phi[x]}{\Gamma\vdash\phi[t]}}
\end{equation}
Well, there is some subtlety with existential introduction. For
example, $\phi[t]:=(\forall x\ldotp t=x)$ where $x\notin FV(t)$. Then
$t$ is free for $x$ in $\phi[-]$, but $\exists x\ldotp\phi[x]$ should
be flagged as problematic. Why?

Well, this situation should never occur because $\phi[x]:=\forall x\ldotp(x=x)$
has $\phi[t]=\forall x\ldotp(x=x)$ which is syntactically different
from $(\forall x\ldotp t=x)$. So an error should be raised, catching
this situation. We add some useful explanatory text in this situation.

A more helpful thing to do would be to rename the bound variable, so
as to avoid this collision.

Also we should raise an exception whenever $t$ and $x$ have different
sorts.
\end{node}

<<Specification for inference rules>>=
val exists_intro : Term.t -> Term.t -> Formula.t -> t -> t;
@

<<Inference rules>>=
fun exists_intro (x : Term.t) (t : Term.t) (phi : Formula.t) (Gamma |- phi_t) =
  if not(Term.is_var(x))
  then raise Fail "exists_intro: x is not a variable"
  else if not(Term.have_same_sort x t)
  then raise Fail "exists_intro: x and t of different sorts"
  else if not(Formula.eq (Formula.subst x t phi) phi_t)
  then (if List.exists (Term.eq x) (Formula.bv phi)
        then raise Fail (
            concat["exists_intro: conclusion mismatch supplied formula ",
                   "(probably x is a bound variable with 't' in its scope)"])
        else raise Fail("exists_intro: conclusion "^
                        (Formula.serialize phi_t)^
                        " mismatch supplied formula "^
                        (Formula.serialize (Formula.subst x t phi))))
  else if not(Formula.free_for t x phi)
  then raise Fail "exists_intro: term is not free for var in formula"
  else Gamma |- (Formula.mk_exists(x, phi))
@ %def Thm.exists_intro

\begin{node}\label{node:kernel:existential-elimination}
Existential elimination takes the form borrowed from the Hilbert
calculus for Intuitionistic logic:
\begin{equation*}
\vcenter{\infer[\exists\mbox{-elim}(x)]{\Gamma\vdash(\exists x\ldotp\phi)\implies\psi}{\Gamma\vdash\phi\implies\psi,&x\notin FV(\psi),&x\notin FV(\Gamma)}}
\end{equation*}
Natural deduction usually takes a different variant for
$\exists$-elim, but we will show that it can be derived from our
inference rules (\S\ref{node:derived:existential-elimination}).
\end{node}

<<Specification for inference rules>>=
val exists_elim : Term.t -> t -> t;
@
<<Inference rules>>=
fun exists_elim (x : Term.t) (Gamma |- A_imp_B) =
  if not(Term.is_var x)
  then raise Fail "exists_elim: x is not a variable"
  else if not(Formula.is_imp A_imp_B)
  then raise Fail "exists_elim: theorem is not an implication"
  else let val (A,B) = Formula.dest_imp A_imp_B;
           fun free_in fm = List.exists (fn y => Term.eq x y) (Formula.fv fm);
       in if free_in B
          then raise Fail "exists_elim: x is free in conclusion of theorem"
          else if List.exists free_in Gamma
          then raise Fail "exists_elim: x is free in hypotheses"
          else Gamma |- (Formula.mk_imp(Formula.mk_exists(x, A), B))
       end;
@ %def Thm.exists_elim

