\begin{node}[Decidable predicates]
We say a predicate $P[x]$ is \define{Decidable} if there exists a
recursive function $f$ such that $\vdash\forall x\ldotp f(x)=0\iff P[x]$.
In this situation, we can infer $\forall x\ldotp P[x]\lor\neg P[x]$.
This only matters for Intuitionistic logic (i.e., our situation).

In $FS_{0}$, we have a weaker notion of primitive recursive functions,
which are any function-sorted term constructed using the
axioms. Primitive recursive functions suffice for our purposes in
determining if a predicate is decidable or not.
This means we have the following additional axiom:
\begin{equation}
\vdash(\exists f:Fun\ldotp\forall x:Ind\ldotp f(x)=0\iff P[x])\implies\forall x:Ind\ldotp P[x]\lor\neg P[x].
\end{equation}
\end{node}

<<Specification for $FS_{0}$ axioms>>=
val axiom_dec : (Term.t -> Formula.t) -> t;
@

<<Axioms for $FS_{0}$>>=
(* axiom_dec : (Term.t -> Formula.t) -> Thm.t *)
fun axiom_dec P =
  let
    val x0 = Term.Var("x0", Sort.IND);
    val vars = (Formula.fv (P x0)) @ (Formula.bv (P x0));
    val x = Term.fresh_var "x" Sort.IND vars;
    val f = Term.fresh_var "f" Sort.FUN vars;
    val premise = Formula.mk_iff(FS0.equal (FS0.app f x)
                                           FS0.zero,
                                P x);
  in
    mk_axiom(Formula.mk_imp(Formula.mk_exists(f, Formula.mk_forall(x, premise)),
                            Formula.mk_forall(x,
                                              Formula.mk_or((P x),
                                                            Formula.mk_not(P x)))))
  end;
@ %def Thm.axiom_dec

\begin{node}
Equality with zero is decidable since $P[x]:=0=x$ corresponds to
the function $f = D\circ(\mathcal{P}(\id, K_{0}, K_{0}, K_{1}))$. Then we have 
$\forall x\ldotp f(x)=0\iff P[x]$, which then implies $\forall x\ldotp x=0\lor x\neq0$.

The problem is that we need an additional axiom asserting
$\forall x\ldotp 0\neq x\implies\bigl(\exists y,z\ldotp x=(y,z)\bigr)$.
The converse is obviously true.
\end{node}

\begin{node}
More generally, if we want to assert the decidability of equality,
then it requires a bit of leg-work. We would first define the
predicate $P[x]:=(\pi_{1}x=\pi_{2}x)$ which corresponds to the
primitive recursive function $f(x)=D(\pi_{1}x,\pi_{2}x,0,1)$,
and then define the predicate $Q[x,y]:=P[(x,y)]$. We want to prove
that $P[x]$ is a decidable predicate (which is obvious), this will
imply the result because $\forall x\ldotp P_{0}[x]\implies\forall x,y\ldotp P_{0}[(x,y)]$ for
any unary predicate $P_{0}$ of individual-sorted terms. 
\end{node}

\begin{problem}[Minor]
The projection functions are ambiguous on $0$, i.e., $P_{1}0$ and
$P_{2}0$ are not specified but should be (and a good choice would be
$P_{1}0=P_{2}0=0$). 
\end{problem}

